        h2.week_number
          span title="Week 7" 7

        .steve
          .header
            h3 Steve's week
            .image
              img src="/images/liberty-week-7.jpg" alt="Libert Grace Brown at 7 weeks old"
          .text
            p Liberty had her six week check-up this week...
            p No, Doc Brown didn’t bundle me into his DeLorean and hurl me one week into the future just so I can tell you about my daughter's uneventful six week check-up. It’s simply that there is a slight overlap with the week Liberty was born and the week when we started this blog. Mystery solved.
            p With my paternity leave now a distant memory, I’m really glad I saved up so many holidays. I can now have one week off every month until Christmas! With the extra time off, we thought that this was a good week to make the pilgrimage up to Lossiemouth to visit my wife’s parents. Just getting out of our driveway was like a military operation. The amount of stuff you have to take with you when you have a baby is mind boggling. There’s the extra suitcase, a car seat, pram with chassis, baby carrier, changing bag, matching luggage, cuddly toy... This probably wasn’t helped by the fact that I needed to take my 27 inch iMac with me as I had some freelance work to do. Eventually we got the car packed up and headed off. 
            p To be honest I was a little worried about the three and a half hour journey, especially because it’s this time of night Liberty can cry inconsolably for no reason. I had visions of my wife breastfeed in a layby and me change Liberty’s nappy on the floor of a grotty service station toilet. Luckily none of that happened and Liberty slept soundly for the entire journey. Who knew traveling with a baby would be so easy?
            p One of the great things about this trip was getting to spend time with my niece and nephew. My niece (who’s seven) was especially excited about our visit as she had been appointed official baby helper. She even wanted to sleep in with my wife and I to help with the night feed. This sounded like a good idea at the time but sharing a double bed with my wife and a seven year old that sleeps like a starfish doesn’t lead to the best nights sleep. Other than that she was brilliant, it was really cute to see her peeking into the pram to check on Liberty.
            p Despite having a load of work to do and feeling pretty run down I was still able to boot-up 'cool uncle mode’ to mess around with my niece, nephew and second cousins. They're aged between two and seven, very boisterous but a lot of fun. When we're play fighting I always end up as the human climbing frame, with all four of them piled on top of me. It was really great to take a break from work and have time with them, I'm looking forward to when Liberty is a bit older so she can join in.
            p All this play fighting, working late and broken sleep is definitely starting to take it’s tole. I can feel myself getting sick. But I can’t. Not yet. I’ve got too much to do.

            h3 What was the best thing?
            p That little sigh Liberty makes after sneezing is super cute.
            
            h3 What was the worst thing?
            p Because of my work I’ve not had much time with my wife or Liberty… sad face.
            
            h3 What have you learnt?
            p When Liberty is crying for 'no reason', check the nappy… it’s usually the nappy. 

            

        .gordon
          .header
            h3 Gordon's week
            .image
              img src="/images/kento-week-7.jpg" alt="Kento McLachlan at 7 weeks old"
          .text
            p I told the Boy that I loved him for the first time.
            p When he was born, I expected a wave of emotion to wash over me. I expected something inside of me to trigger and my view of life to fundamentally change. It never did and at the moment he entered this world, I felt nothing. No joy. No pride. No fear. No remorse. No love.
            p Last night, I looked down at him as I held him in the dark. I imagined him growing up and giving him all the things from a father that I never had; reading to him, playing with him, teaching him, guiding him.
            p I told him I loved him and then I cried.
            
            h3 What was the best thing?
            p I’ve started to get a lot of attention from hot girls and crazy people when taking the Boy out by myself. I’m ok with this.
            
            h3 What was the worst thing?
            p The Boy has started making noises like a baby goat. Is this normal? I’m assuming any noise is good noise even if does make me feel like I’m living on a farm.
            
            h3 What have you learnt?
            p People assume your infant is like a prize dog at Crufts and that they every right to peer and poke at it.
            
            h3 Any additional comments?
            p People who park in parent and child spaces without a kid in the back of their car (an empty child seat DOES NOT COUNT) deserve to burn in the depths of fucking Hell.

