      article.week#week8 data-week-number="8"

        h2.week_number
          span title="Week 8" 8

        .steve
          .header
            h3 Steve's week
            .image
              img src="/images/liberty-week-8.jpg" alt="Libert Grace Brown at 8 weeks old"
          .text
            p The late nights working, early starts and broken sleep have finally caught up with me… I’m sick. Really sick.
            p Liberty’s baby flu has mutated into some kind of baby-flu/man-flu hybrid and it’s hit me like a baseball bat to the head. There’s only one thing for it, take as much Night Nurse as my body could handle, cocoon myself in a duvet then hibernate for 16 and a half hours. My wife was amazing through all this, because on top of looking after a sick winey baby she managed to take care of all Liberty’s needs too.
            p When Liberty got sick it was hard to know what’s normal for a sick baby and what to really worry about. She has a bit of a temperature and coughed up some weird green slimey thing that looked like a discarded alien from an episode of Dr Who, so we took the precaution and got her checked out. Thankfully there wasn’t anything to worry about and much like when we have the flu she’ll just have to keep it until it gets better. Still, it was good to hear there were a few things I could do to make it easier for her. The most interesting of these has to be the nasal aspirator, or more affectionately know as the 'boggie sucker'. To operate this little contraption you really have to detach yourself from the job at hand. Even though there is a microfilter between said boggies and my pursed lips, I still gag at the thought. I can only hope she learns to blow her own nose sooner rather than later.
            p Even though I’ve been out of action for a few days I’m now feeling much better, just in time too. After all her nursing duties my wife was shattered and deserved a well earned rest. So when Liberty wouldn’t sleep at 3am and remembering there was a 50ml bottle of breastmilk in the fridge, I decided to go it alone. After all, I’m now well versed in the art of bottle feeding. In the living room, under the cover of darkness she polished off the bottle in no time and winded like a champ. I was then able to take her up to bed and put her down without waking my wife. Nice.

            h3 What was the best thing?
            p I still get a real kick out of bottle feeding and I got to do it a couple of times this week.
            
            h3 What was the worst thing?
            p Having zero energy and feeling pretty useless for most of the week.
            
            h3 What have you learnt?
            p An eight week old baby can handle the flu a lot better than I can...

            

        .gordon
          .header
            h3 Gordon's week
            .image
              img src="/images/kento-week-8.jpg" alt="Kento McLachlan at 8 weeks old"
          .text
            p The Boy has started to smile.
			
            p A once emotionless potato has now suddenly bloomed into an ever-so-slightly self-aware life form. Or so the Wife thinks. Convinced he smiles only when he’s happy, showered with affection or attention, she believes the connection is undeniable.

            p Personally, I have my suspicions. After many hours of deeply scientific study, I’ve noted a direct correlation between his smiling and when he shits, pisses or otherwise evacuates himself.
			
            p Simple pleasures.
            
            h3 What was the best thing?
            p Finally getting some sort of feedback from the Boy. The flesh Tamagotchi is starting to interact.
            
            h3 What was the worst thing?
            p Honestly, nothing. It was all really easy
            
            h3 What have you learnt?
            p It’s amazing how happiness is so contagious. Just like the disease that is stress, happiness can spread with a smile and lift the darkest day.

            p Forget pet therapy, they should provide babies on the NHS to the clinically depressed.
            
            h3 Any additional comments?
            p Pushing a pram around has given me a strange appreciation for lifts in shops. Along with a newly founded hatred for unhindered able-bodied people who take them up one floor instead of an escalator or flight of stairs. 

            p This is why you’re fat, Britain.

