        .steve
          .header
            h3 Steve's week
            .image
              img src="/images/liberty-week-9.jpg" alt="Libert Grace Brown at 9 weeks old"
          .text
            p I wasn't looking forward to this week. This is the week Liberty gets her first set of immunisations.
            p Now I'm not someone who's scared of needles. I’ve had a tetanus shot, immunisations for holidays and given blood on a number of occasions. However the prospect of holding down my nine week old daughter while a nurse jabs her with a needle wasn't something I was looking forward to.
            p Liberty was totally oblivious of course, so I held her legs as the nurse stood there, poised, ready to stab her… Three times… Twice in the same leg… needless to say she wasn't happy, but luckily this only lasted for about 10 seconds, then she went to sleep. Or at least she was pretending to sleep, in the hope that no one would do that to her again. I’m sure they won’t, well not this week anyway.
            p Immunisations aside this has been a really good week. In fact I’ve just realised that Liberty now understands the difference between night and day. She’s now power naps during the day and sleeps from midnight until 6am, in two three hour blocks. I can only put this down to a strict no talking policy when she wakes up in the middle of the night. Turnaround time is good too, we can now get her changed, refuelled and back off in 20 minutes. Beat that easyjet! Although she still has her ‘witching hour’ at around 9pm where she cries for 30 minutes for no reason. Inevitably after all that crying she’ll fall asleep in your arms, then the fun begins. As it turns out there’s an art to placing a sleeping baby into bed. 
            p I’m Indiana Jones in the Temple of Doom, ready switch the Golden Idol with that perfectly weighted bag of sand. I make my move, then much like our intrepid Indy, I hold my breath in anticipation… Did I succeed? Or am I about to be flattened by a steamrolling bolder of screams, sent to crush any hope of a good night's sleep? No, not tonight. I think I’ve finally cracked it.


            h3 What was the best thing?
            p Every weekend has been super busy up until now, however this weekend was just for the three of us. So, what did we do? We treated Liberty to her first trip to the world famous Dobbies Garden Centre (she wasn't impressed), had some lunch then did a bit of shopping. It felt great to get out and about as a family, pushing the pram like the proud parent I am. It also gave me more confidence about venturing out and about. I think I'm almost ready to take Liberty out on my own... Well almost.

            
            h3 What was the worst thing?
            p Holding Liberty while she got her immunisation injections. #TotesObvs, as the kids say.
            
            h3 What have you learnt?
            p There is a very specific way to put Liberty into her SnüzPod so she doesn’t wake up.

            

        .gordon
          .header
            h3 Gordon's week
            .image
              img src="/images/kento-week-9.jpg" alt="Kento McLachlan at 9 weeks old"
          .text
            p I didn’t see the Boy much this week.

            p A trip to Amsterdam to speak at the international Fronteers web conference with my co-directors took me away from home for almost the whole week. To ensure the Wife was well looked after, my mother moved into our apartment in my absence.

            p Of course, daily photos from the Wife - usually accompanied by demands for money - kept me in touch. ‘Money man’ she calls me in front the Boy in the I’m-joking-no-not-really kind of way. 

            p I don’t mind. ‘Nappy lady’ has a nice ring to it.
            
            h3 What was the best thing?
            p Getting to speak at (and attend) Fronteers. It was incredible. It was also nice to be able to bond with two good friends.
            
            h3 What was the worst thing?
            p Forgetting I have a family.
            
            h3 What have you learnt?
            p The Wife and Boy operate just fine without me. Aside from my wallet and a steady stream of cash, I bring very little to the table. Given we haven’t had a single argument, tense situation or stressful moment since the Boy was born, it seems to work rather well. I’m contemplating becoming an icon for parents across the globe.
            
            h3 Any additional comments?
            p Travelling for work invokes mixed emotions. A conference like Fronteers can be tremendously rewarding but then being away from home is never fun. I was inspired by one of the speakers who just packed up his six month old daughter and brought her with him. The ‘just get on with life’ attitude gives me hope.

            p Next time.

